{"title_page": "Sagittal abdominal diameter", "text_new": "[[Image:SupineAbdominalHt.jpg|thumb|right|250px|SAH measure using supine abdominal height]]\n'''Sagittal abdominal diameter''' ('''SAD''') is a measure of [[Visceral fat|visceral obesity]], the amount of fat in the gut region. SAD is the distance from the small of the back to the upper abdomen. SAD may be measured when standing<ref name=pmid17041127>{{cite journal |first1=Carlos |last1=Iribarren |first2=Jeanne A. |last2=Darbinian |first3=Joan C. |last3=Lo |first4=Bruce H. |last4=Fireman |first5=Alan S. |last5=Go |year=2006 |title=Value of the Sagittal Abdominal Diameter in Coronary Heart Disease Risk Assessment: Cohort Study in a Large, Multiethnic Population |journal=American Journal of Epidemiology |volume=164 |issue=12 |pages=1150\u20139 |doi=10.1093/aje/kwj341 |pmid=17041127}}</ref> or supine.<ref name=pmid17391519>{{cite journal |first1=Helena |last1=Petersson |first2=Achraf |last2=Daryani |first3=Ulf |last3=Ris\u00e9rus |year=2007 |title=Sagittal abdominal diameter as a marker of inflammation and insulin resistance among immigrant women from the Middle East and native Swedish women: a cross-sectional study |journal=Cardiovascular Diabetology |volume=6 |pages=10 |pmid=17391519 |pmc=1847804 |doi=10.1186/1475-2840-6-10}}</ref> SAD may be measured at any point from the narrowest point between the last rib and the iliac crests to the midpoint of the iliac crests.<ref name=pmid17041127 /><ref name=pmid17391519 /><ref name=\"doi101111\">{{cite journal |first1=HA |last1=de Almeida Paula |first2=R |last2=de C\u00e1ssia Lanes Ribeiro |first3=LEFP |last3=de Lima Rosado |first4=MV |last4=Abranches |first5=S |last5=do Carmo Castro Franceschini |date=31 July 2012 |title=Relationship between waist circumference and supine abdominal height measured at different anatomical sites and cardiometabolic risk factors in older women |journal=Journal of Human Nutrition and Dietetics|volume=25 |issue=6 |pages=563\u20138 | doi=10.1111/j.1365-277X.2012.01267.x|pmid=23173640 }}</ref>\n\nSAD is a strong predictor of [[coronary disease]], with higher values indicating increased risk independent of [[body mass index|BMI]].<ref name=pmid17041127 />\n\nFor persons of normal BMI, SAD should be under {{convert|25|cm|in}}. The amount this measure exceeds {{convert|30|cm|in}} correlates to increased [[Cardiovascular disease|cardiovascular]] risk and [[insulin resistance]].<ref name=pmid17391519 /> SAD measure of men in their 40s, greater than 25&nbsp;cm, also predicts significantly higher risk of [[Alzheimer's disease]] 30 years later.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=1057\u201364 |doi=10.1212/01.wnl.0000306313.89165.ef |title=Central obesity and increased risk of dementia more than three decades later |year=2008 |last1=Whitmer |first1=R. A. |last2=Gustafson |first2=D. R. |last3=Barrett-Connor |first3=E. |last4=Haan |first4=M. N. |last5=Gunderson |first5=E. P. |last6=Yaffe |first6=K. |journal=Neurology |volume=71 |issue=14 |pmid=18367704}}</ref> An article in [[Annals of Neurology]] links visceral fat to lower brain volume<ref>{{cite journal |pages=136\u201344 |doi=10.1002/ana.22062 |title=Visceral fat is associated with lower brain volume in healthy middle-aged adults |year=2010 |last1=Debette |first1=St\u00e9phanie |last2=Beiser |first2=Alexa |last3=Hoffmann |first3=Udo |last4=Decarli |first4=Charles |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Christopher J. |last6=Massaro |first6=Joseph M. |last7=Au |first7=Rhoda |last8=Himali |first8=Jayandra J. |last9=Wolf |first9=Philip A. |last10=Fox |first10=Caroline S. |last11=Seshadri |first11=Sudha |journal=Annals of Neurology |pmid=20695006 |pmc=2933649 |volume=68|issue=2 }}</ref>\n\nA related measurement is ''Supine Abdominal Height'' (SAH), the abdominal height as measured in the [[supine position]].<ref>{{cite journal |pages=2041\u20136 |doi=10.2337/diacare.27.8.2041 |title=Sagittal Abdominal Diameter Is a Strong Anthropometric Marker of Insulin Resistance and Hyperproinsulinemia in Obese Men |year=2004 |last1=Riserus |first1=Ulf |last2=\u00c4rnl\u00f6v |first2=Johan |last3=Brismar |first3=Kerstin |last4=Zethelius |first4=Bj\u00f6rn |last5=Berglund |first5=Lars |last6=Vessby |first6=Bengt |journal=Diabetes Care |volume=27 |issue=8 |pmid=15277437|doi-access=free }}</ref> The SAH method is easier for self-monitoring, but gives slightly lower results due to gravity; the values are not directly comparable.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Central obesity]]\n* [[Body fat percentage]]\n*[[Index of Central Obesity]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Classification of obesity]]\n[[Category:Obesity]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:SupineAbdominalHt.jpg|thumb|right|250px|SAH measure using supine abdominal height]]\n'''Sagittal abdominal diameter''' ('''SAD''') is a measure of [[Visceral fat|visceral obesity]], the amount of fat in the gut region. SAD is the distance from the small of the back to the upper abdomen. SAD may be measured when standing<ref name=pmid17041127>{{cite journal |first1=Carlos |last1=Iribarren |first2=Jeanne A. |last2=Darbinian |first3=Joan C. |last3=Lo |first4=Bruce H. |last4=Fireman |first5=Alan S. |last5=Go |year=2006 |title=Value of the Sagittal Abdominal Diameter in Coronary Heart Disease Risk Assessment: Cohort Study in a Large, Multiethnic Population |journal=American Journal of Epidemiology |volume=164 |issue=12 |pages=1150\u20139 |doi=10.1093/aje/kwj341 |pmid=17041127}}</ref> or supine.<ref name=pmid17391519>{{cite journal |first1=Helena |last1=Petersson |first2=Achraf |last2=Daryani |first3=Ulf |last3=Ris\u00e9rus |year=2007 |title=Sagittal abdominal diameter as a marker of inflammation and insulin resistance among immigrant women from the Middle East and native Swedish women: a cross-sectional study |journal=Cardiovascular Diabetology |volume=6 |pages=10 |pmid=17391519 |pmc=1847804 |doi=10.1186/1475-2840-6-10}}</ref> SAD may be measured at any point from the narrowest point between the last ri